mobile games such as Puzzles and Dragons, which eat away their precious time. They sit with their ring-pinging mobiles throughout the day, awaiting for their next game session, preventing them from giving their academic activities due attention.

Young kids have found yet another hobby of I-maging on their hand-held gaming set. On one click, money flows into their pocket through a myriad of bonuses called QR-Cash.

This is not unusual behavior, many people in my Bhutanese peer group have succumbed to this type of lifestyle, irresponsibly creating privileged users of QR-Cash.

A common type of luxury our parents could not afford, hard money or as we called it, the “bunka”, exists only in mobile phones, and are mined in batches. A burdensome activity compared to paper money, mobile money can be obtained by downloading various apps and purchasing items online.

Parents would be alarmed at the thought that children would squander their limited pocket money on mobiles. It is difficult to have a chat with a teen when excited about your colourful cash accumulation on your mobile.

Many do not realise that mobile money can prove to be a stumbling block when it comes to financial life. Downloading gaming applications every day and enjoying bonuses may very well be regarded as having a job. But you can’t really compare earning QR-Cash with a real job. People forget that games are never free. There is always a catch to make you feel a victim of an unstoppable addiction.
